Scatter plots with many points

Author

Michael Stadler

Summary

This document illustrates how to use ggplot2 to:

  • make a scatter plot with many data points that shows the density of points without saturation
  • that is fast to open and edit
  • that can be stored into file with a small size without loss in quality

Prepare data

Run the following code to prepare the data used in this document:

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
    library(ggplot2)
    library(tibble)
})

# built-in `dimanonds` dataset from the `ggplot2` package (see ?ggplot2::diamonds)
tibble(diamonds)

Create figure

Load packages

Code 
library(ggplot2)
library(scattermore)

Plot

Letâs first create a simple scatter plot to illustrate the problems. The diamonds dataset has 53940 observations. If stored into a vectorized graphics device such as pdf() or svg(), the file will be large (each observation is individually represented as graphic elements) and slow to open or arrange. Furthermore, the high number of data points leads to saturation and we do not seed the underlying density of data points.

# create base plot
p0 <- ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
    labs(x = "Weight of the diamond (carat)", y = "Price (US dollars)") +
    theme_bw(20) +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          legend.position = "bottom")
p0 + geom_point()

A simple way to improve these issue is to use transparency, so that overlapping observations lead to darker colors. However, this does not solve the âmany pointsâ problem yet.

Code 
# ... with transparency
p0 + geom_point(color = alpha("black", 0.02))

A simple way to solve also the âmany pointsâ problem is to not show all individual observations anymore, and instead show for example a heat map of the local density of points.

Code 
# ... with marginal density plots by number of cylinders
p0 + geom_density_2d_filled(bins = 48) +
    coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE) +
    theme(legend.position = "none")

The linear contour levels or color intervals (controlled by bins or breaks) may not work well in a case like ours, where the density is very high in some regions and low in others. You can use breaks to create non-linear intervals (here combined with ndensity so that we know the range of densities: [0, 1]) and with panel.background to make the zero-density area dark blue.

Code 
# ... with marginal density plots by number of cylinders
p0 + geom_density_2d_filled(contour_var = "ndensity",
                            breaks = exp(seq(log(1e-4), log(1), length.out = 64))) +
    coord_cartesian(expand = FALSE) +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          panel.background = element_rect(fill = hcl.colors(64)[1]))

Finally, if you really prefer to show individual observations and need something that will scale to millions of points without getting slow or hard to use, there is a solution for that too.

Code 
# ... with marginal violin and labelled data points
p0 + geom_scattermore(pointsize = 2, alpha = 0.02)

Remarks

  • scattermore does its magic by rendering the geom_point layer into a bitmap, while keeping all the other layers as they are, allowing you to for example zoom into a plot and not lose readability of the axes.
  • scattermore provides two ggplot2 layers: geom_scattermore() (which behaves just like geom_point(), and geom_scattermost() which avoids much of the overhead and thus is even more efficient, at the price that it has a slightly different interface and for example needs to get the data directly as the xy argument.
  • An alternative, maybe even more convenient drop-in replacement for geom_point() and other ggplot2 geoms that follows a similar strategy is geom_point_rast() from the ggrastr package. This package also provides the rasterize() function that can take any existing ggplot2 plot object and rasterize suitable layer in it. Compared to scattermore, ggrastr does not seem to be as fast and scale as well, though.
